This feature and documents are in BETA, please reach out to support@yeshid.com if you run into any issues.What you’re writingYou’re writing a single JavaScript function named run(context).run(context) must return true for the run to be considered successful.The script runs in a safe, limited JavaScript environment (ES5.1 only).Minimum required script function run(context) { 
 console.log("Starting script"); 
 return true; 
 } 
———1) Runtime rules (important)ES5.1 only: no let, const, arrow functions, classes, async/await, template literals.run(context) is required.Return true to pass. Anything else fails the run.———2) Available globalsYou can use these without importing anything:consoleconsole.log(...)console.warn(...)console.error(...)These show up in the Console tab after a test run.fetch(url, options)Synchronous HTTP request (not async).Returns an object with:status (number)ok (boolean)text() → stringjson() → parsed JSON objectheaders.get(name)headers.has(name)headers.keys()headers.entries()Example: function run(context) { 
 var auth = context.get("auth") || {}; 
 var url = auth.baseUrl + "/users"; 
 var resp = fetch(url, { 
 method: "GET", 
 headers: { 
 "Authorization": auth.tokenType + " " + auth.token 
 } 
 }); 

 if (!resp.ok) { 
 console.error("Request failed:", resp.status, resp.text()); 
 return false; 
 } 

 var data = resp.json(); 
 console.log("Fetched", data.length, "users"); 
 return true; 
 } 
———3) Context data you can accessUse context.get(key) to read injected values.Common keysauth → provisioning auth info (token, baseUrl, api key, etc).input → the current account/user data (for user actions).properties → any key/values you defined in the Properties tab.Access examples function run(context) { 
 var auth = context.get("auth"); 
 var input = context.get("input"); 
 var props = context.get("properties"); 

 console.log("Base URL:", auth && auth.baseUrl); 
 console.log("Account email:", input && input.account && input.account.user && input.account.user.email); 
 console.log("Custom property:", props && props.region); 
 return true; 
 } 
For Script Engine scripts, context.get('auth') can include these properties:baseUrltokentokenTypeheaderKeyheaderValuePrefixapiKeyapiKeyNameapiKeyLocationusernamepasswordBy auth type:OAuth2: token, optional tokenType, headerKey, headerValuePrefixBearer: token, tokenType = "bearer"API key: apiKey, apiKeyName, apiKeyLocationBasic: username, passwordIf nothing is configured, context.get('auth') may be absent.4) Using script actionsActions are helper functions that the platform exposes (like importUsers).See the Library tab for actions, parameters, and return types.Click Insert to drop a snippet into your script.Use autocomplete by typing the action name.Example: function run(context) { 
 importUsers([ 
 { 
 externalId: "123", 
 email: "user@example.com", 
 displayName: "Example User" 
 } 
 ]); 
 return true; 
 } 
———5) Testing your scriptClick Test to run in test mode:Actions are validated but not executed.Network requests are executed.Output appears in Console, Network, and Actions tabs.If a line number appears in logs, click it to jump to the code line.———6) PublishingYou must pass a test run before you can publish.Publish makes the script active and versioned.———7) VersioningEvery publish creates a version.Use Versions tab to revert.———8) Properties (key/value)Use Properties to store configuration values for the script:They are accessible via context.get("properties").You can mark a property as Encrypted (stored as a secret).Example: function run(context) { 
 var props = context.get("properties") || {}; 
 var apiKey = props.apiKey; // encrypted values are returned decrypted here 
 console.log("Has API key:", !!apiKey); 
 return true; 
 } 
———9) Common errors“run(context) must return true” → return true explicitly.Parse error → ES5.1 only (no modern JS syntax).Publish disabled → run Test successfully first.
